17 SECTION 2. IC 20-26-22.1 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
2026 IN 138—LS 6538/DI 152

2
1 AS A NEW CHAPTER TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
2 JULY 1, 2026]:
3 Chapter 22.1. School Chaplains
4 Sec. 1. As used in this chapter, "school" includes the following:
5 (1) A school maintained by a school corporation.
6 (2) A charter school.
7 Sec. 2. As used in this chapter, "school chaplain" refers to an
8 individual who meets the qualifications described in section 3 of
9 this chapter and whose primary responsibility is to provide advice,
10 guidance, and support services to students and employees of a
11 school.
12 Sec. 3. A school principal or superintendent may employ, or
13 approve as a volunteer, a school chaplain if the individual:
14 (1) obtains an expanded criminal history check and expanded
15 child protection index check as described in IC 20-26-5-10;
16 (2) has:
17 (A) never been convicted of an offense listed in
18 IC 20-28-5-8(c) or described in IC 20-28-5-8(d); or
19 (B) been convicted of an offense described in clause (A) but
20 the individual's conviction was reversed, vacated, or set
21 aside on appeal; and
22 (3) meets one (1) of the following:
23 (A) Has a baccalaureate degree in divinity, theology,
24 religious studies, or a related field and at least four (4)
25 years of counseling experience.
26 (B) Has a baccalaureate degree in divinity, theology,
27 religious studies or a related field and at least two (2) years
28 of counseling experience while working towards a master's
29 degree in divinity, theology, religious studies, or a related
30 field.
31 (C) Has a master's degree in divinity, theology, religious
32 studies, or a related field and at least two (2) years of
33 counseling experience.
34 Sec. 4. A school chaplain may do the following:
35 (1) Provide secular advice, guidance, and support services to
36 a student or employee of the school.
37 (2) Provide nonsecular advice, guidance, and support services
38 only if one (1) of the following applies:
39 (A) If the student is an emancipated minor or an adult, the
40 student receiving services provides permission allowing the
41 nonsecular advice, guidance, and support services.
42 (B) For an employee receiving services, the employee
2026 IN 138—LS 6538/DI 152

3
1 provides permission allowing the nonsecular advice,
2 guidance, and support services.
3 (C) If the student is an unemancipated minor, a parent of
4 the student and the student receiving services provide
5 permission allowing the nonsecular advice, guidance, and
6 support services.
7 Sec. 5. (a) Except as provided in subsection (b), IC 20-33-7.5,
8 IC 31-32-11-1, and IC 31-33-5:
9 (1) communications made by a student to a school chaplain as
10 a school chaplain are privileged and confidential; and
11 (2) a school chaplain is not required to disclose
12 communications described in subdivision (1).
13 (b) A school chaplain shall disclose to a school counselor
14 communications made by a student to the school chaplain if the
15 communications concern:
16 (1) self-harm of the student; or
17 (2) an intention to harm others.
